mgur.com/gallery/qp2Zbfg</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/cET93jp.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/qp2Zbfg</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[pilomotor]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Pharaoh Seti I and the boast about the Sinai nomads</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/6eoBfNO</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/AwraAGa.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Over 3300 years ago Seti I of Egypt fought the bedouins of Sinai, and would not hold back about it.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/wXipLpa.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Egypt was already an ancient and great power in the late Bronze Age, but by 1300 BCE it had suffered decades of internal turmoil and a loss of influence abroad.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/l63FCyS.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Its dominion along the upper Mediterranean coast and in modern Syria had been supplanted by the mighty rival Hittite Empire (purple). 

Closer to home rebellious vassalls in Caanan no longer heeded the word of the Pharaohs, while the roads were raided by desert nomads.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/UB3ZNL7.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Pharaoh Seti I came to power presumably in 1294 or 1290 BCE. Though not as famous as his son, Ramesses II, Seti was an able statesman and general. 

Indeed, though his Nineteenth Dynasty was devoted to the god Amun whom they called their father, his own name refers to Set, a god of disorder and violence.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/pqPHr3e.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>In year 1 of his regn Seti decided to handle the threats along the Way of Horus (yellow), also known as the Horus Military Road, and later Via Maris. The Way of Horus went from northern Egypt along the coast through Sinai (red) into Caanan.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/AzUnTWK.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>On the Sinai Peninsula lived the bedouin Shasu. They raided the road as well as threatened access to rich mines on the Peninsula. 

Shasu warriors were able with spears and axes, posing a serious threat to caravans, but now they faced the retribution of an empire (art from Luwian Studies).</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/kkHLX63.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>The main Egyptian force was light infantry, including foreign mercenaries. with bronze spears, maces, swords and axes. The archers, of who Nubian mercenaries were praised, had powerful composite bows. 

War-chariots was the pride of Bronze Age armies but only the upper class and the state could afford the horses and equipment required, as well as heavier armour.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/QyqdG6i.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Seti recorded his wars on a wall at the Karnak Temple Complex in Egypt [above he is seen in a chariot]. There is told how as "They do not obey the laws of the Palace." the Pharaoh moved against the Shasu. He fought them from the fortress of Sile [an Egyptian fortress on the Way of Horus] east into Caanan.

"His Majesty seized them like a terrifying lion, turning them to corpses throughout their valleys, wallowling in their blood as if (they) had never existed."</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/pZFFTDx.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>"Everyone that escapes his fingers says: 'His might toward distant countries is the might of his father Amun, who hath assigned to him a victorious valor in the countries'."

Above are seen Shasu flee and surrender. After this victory, that may have been a one-sided affair despite the attempt to make it a glorious achievement, Seti went on to bring the Caanan vassals to heel.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/x0syO4Y.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>The Pharaoh would command armies north into Lebanon, west into Libya, and south into Nubia [above he slays prisoners, as the kings repeatedly portrayed themselves, with a mace]. 

Seti I was instrumental in restoring order in, and influence abroad to, Egypt, until his reigned ended in 1279 BCE; because also to a Pharaoh came the day when he no longer existed.

